<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="151" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1303,2014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1303,1330]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species can be differentiated from the other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1933" box="[981,1133,1304,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudastenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[981,1133,1304,1330]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Pseudastenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with elongate elytra by the totally light brown coloration of elytra and the only slightly darker coloration of the head. In contrast to all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1933" box="[151,303,1376,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudastenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,303,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Pseudastenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, the apical sclerites of the aedeagus have several hooks pointing laterally and not only one hook pointing backwards (
<figureCitation box="[449,526,1411,1438]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–54" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1895,1920]" captionTargetBox="[232,1346,220,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[164,1424,181,1869]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 48–54. Aedeagus of Pseudastenus, dorsal and lateral view, respectively, figures 51–54 including microscopic detail of basal slerites. 48. P. ribeirocostae sp. nov.; 49. P. ferrugineus sp. nov.; 50. P. latus sp. nov.; 51. P. barretoi; 52. P. oculatus sp. nov.; 53. P. amazonicus sp. nov.; 54. P. schubarti sp. nov. Scale bar: 0.3 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3724309" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3724309/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Fig 53</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="151" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1303,2014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1447,1474]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Description.</emphasis>
Body length: 
<quantity box="[507,611,1448,1474]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.89" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="2.89">2.89 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: head light brown; pronotum lighter brown than head, nearly yellow; elytra slightly darker brown than pronotum, but lighter than head; abdomen brown; femurs brown, tibiae, tarsi and antennae yellow (
<figureCitation box="[451,535,1520,1546]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–45" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1932,1957]" captionTargetBox="[197,1381,213,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1906]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 40–45. Dorsal view. 40. Pseudastenus ribeirocostae sp. nov.; 41. P. ferrugineus sp. nov.; 42. P. latus sp. nov.; 43. P. oculatus sp. nov.; 44. P. amazonicus sp. nov.; 45. P. schubarti sp. nov. Scale bars: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3724303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3724303/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). Head: 
<quantity box="[628,728,1520,1546]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="0.37">0.37 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[798,898,1520,1546]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="0.41">0.41 mm</quantity>
wide; eyes moderately short; 0.24 times as long as total length of head; half as long as postocular length. Pronotum: 
<quantity box="[917,1017,1556,1582]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="0.37">0.37 mm</quantity>
long; 
<quantity box="[1088,1189,1556,1582]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="0.46">0.46 mm</quantity>
wide; widest near anterior obtuse angles; apical and posterior margin curved; sides slightly convergentposteriad; with long black seta, each marking obtuse angles. Elytra: 
<quantity box="[553,652,1628,1654]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" unit="mm" value="0.46">0.46 mm</quantity>
long, 
