<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="151" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1303,2014]" box="[199,1327,1844,1870]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1844,1870]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name derived from the Brazilian state of 
<collectingRegion box="[937,1058,1844,1870]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, where it was collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1303,2014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,468,1879,1906]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Geographical records.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Busanello &amp; Irmler &amp; Caron" authorityYear="2020" box="[477,772,1880,1906]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudastenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonicus">
<emphasis box="[477,772,1880,1906]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Pseudastenus amazonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in Central Amazonia along the Rio Solimões, Amazonas (
<collectingCountry box="[284,358,1916,1943]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Brazil</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1303,2014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,397,1951,1978]" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">Biological notes.</emphasis>
The two specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Busanello &amp; Irmler &amp; Caron" authorityYear="2020" box="[672,834,1953,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudastenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonicus">
<emphasis box="[672,834,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="151">P. amazonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected in the inundation forest and floating meadows of the Rio Solimões.
</paragraph>
